You are working in a Java 21 + Spring Boot 3.5 (Maven) monolith: Jewelry_Management.
Primary packages observed under `com.example.jewelry_management`: controller, service, service.impl, repository, repository.specification, model, dto, form, mapper, security, config, exception, utils, enums.

Follow these rules when making changes.

## 1) Codebase intent & boundaries
- Keep a standard Spring layering: controller -> service (interface) -> service.impl -> repository -> database.
- Controllers must stay thin: request parsing/validation, auth context, calling service, mapping response, HTTP codes only.
- Business logic belongs in service layer; persistence logic stays in repositories/specifications.
- Do not expose JPA entities (`model/*`) directly in API responses. Use DTOs (`dto/*`) and mappers (`mapper/*` or ModelMapper where already used).

## 2) Project conventions (match existing structure)
- New controllers go in `controller/` and should be annotated with `@RestController` (or `@Controller` only for Thymeleaf views).
- New service interfaces go in `service/`, implementations in `service/impl/`. Prefer constructor injection.
- New repositories go in `repository/` and extend Spring Data interfaces; keep specifications in `repository/specification/`.
- New request payload classes go in `form/` and should be validated with `jakarta.validation` annotations.
- New response payload classes go in `dto/res/` (or existing DTO folders) and should not include sensitive fields.
- Enums go in `enums/`, shared helpers in `utils/`, security components in `security/`, configuration in `config/`.

## 3) Spring + DI style
- Prefer constructor injection; avoid field injection.
- Prefer `@ConfigurationProperties` for structured config over many scattered `@Value`s.
- Avoid static global state; keep beans stateless unless justified.

## 4) REST API guidelines
- Use consistent naming: plural nouns for collections (e.g., `/products`), resource identifiers as path params.
- Return appropriate status codes: 200/201/204; use 400 for validation errors, 401/403 for auth/permission, 404 for missing resources.
- Input validation: use `@Valid` on request bodies and validate query params; never trust client input.
- Keep response shape consistent across endpoints (re-use existing response DTO patterns).

## 5) Security (Spring Security + JWT)
- Never log secrets: JWTs, passwords, API keys, DB credentials, mail credentials, payment keys.
- Any auth-related change must be reviewed for: token expiry, refresh/rotation (if present), and proper 401/403 behavior.
- CORS/CSRF changes must be intentional and documented in the change description.

## 6) JPA/Hibernate & performance
- Default to `FetchType.LAZY` for relationships; avoid eager loading that explodes queries.
- Watch for N+1 queries in service methods returning lists; consider fetch joins / entity graphs / projections if needed.
- Use pagination for endpoints returning collections.
- Wrap multi-step write operations in `@Transactional` at the service layer (avoid transactional logic in controllers).

## 7) Exceptions & logging
- Prefer centralized exception handling (existing `exception/*`) over try/catch in controllers.
- Log with SLF4J; include context (user id/order id) when helpful, but never sensitive data.

## 8) Configuration & secrets
- This repo uses environment variables (see `application.yml`) and Dotenv loading in `JewelryManagementApplication`.
- Do not commit `.env` or any secrets. If a feature needs new config, add it to `application.yml` with an env-var placeholder.
- Avoid putting long prose/prompts or non-secret documentation inside `.env`.

## 9) AI/LangChain4j integration
- Keep AI provider keys and model configuration in config classes under `config/` and read from env vars.
- Ensure fallbacks exist for AI calls (timeouts, graceful degradation) and avoid blocking heavy calls on request threads where possible.

## 10) Change safety checklist (do before finishing)
- Update/introduce DTOs + mapping when modifying API payloads.
- Ensure security filters/config still allow intended public endpoints only.
- Run tests/build when feasible: `mvn -q test` (or at least compile) and fix compilation errors.

## 11) Code generation checklist
Khi generate code mới, luôn tạo đủ:
- [ ] Form class (trong `form/`) với @Valid annotations
- [ ] DTO response (trong `dto/`) không chứa sensitive fields  
- [ ] Mapper method (trong `mapper/`)
- [ ] Service interface method
- [ ] ServiceImpl method với @Transactional nếu write operation
- [ ] Repository method nếu cần custom query
- [ ] Controller endpoint mỏng (chỉ gọi service + trả DTO)

## 12) Jewelry domain context
- Các entity chính: Product, Order, Customer, Invoice (thêm đúng tên thực tế)
- Giá tiền dùng BigDecimal, không dùng double/float
- Trọng lượng vàng/đá quý cần precision cao
- Audit fields (createdAt, updatedAt, createdBy) phải có trên entity quan trọng

## 13) Naming hints
- Form: CreateProductForm, UpdateOrderForm
- DTO: ProductDTO, OrderResponseDTO  
- Exception: ResourceNotFoundException, DuplicateResourceException
